## Trends in Open, Laparoscopic, and Robotic Approaches to Colorectal Operations

Luv N. Hajirawala, MD, MS 1 , Claudia Leonardi, PhD 2 , Guy R. Orangio, MD 1 , Kurt G. Davis, MD 1 , and Jeffrey S. Barton, MD 1

## Abstract

The use of robotic approach has gained momentum in colorectal surgery. We analyzed the trends in the adoption of robotic-assisted platform (RAP) for colorectal surgery over a 6-year period (2013-2018) using the American College of Surgeons National Surgical Quality Improvement Project. We assessed yearly prevalence of robotic, laparoscopic, and open approaches, and evaluated trends in the adoption of RAP across age, gender, BMI, and American Society of Anesthesiology (ASA) subgroups. Overall, the frequency of open, laparoscopic, and robotic approach was 36%, 46.8%, and 7.8%, respectively. While the use of laparoscopic cases remained stable over the study period, the prevalence of RAP increased from 2.8% to 11.4%. This was accompanied by a concomitant decline in the use of open approach, from 40.8% to 33%. The use of RAP also increased across all age, gender, BMI, and ASA subgroups. Robotic-assisted platform is increasingly utilized for higher risk, older, and obese patients, allowing more patients to receive minimally invasive colorectal surgery.

## Keywords

colorectal, gastrointestinal, general surgery, minimally invasive surgery, robotic surgery

Minimally invasive surgery (MIS) has gained acceptance in colorectal surgery (CRS), and laparoscopy now accounts for nearly half of the cases performed each year. 1 Robotic-assisted platforms (RAPs) have become an important approach since their introduction in the early 2000s. Robotic-assisted platforms claim several clinical advantages, including improved dexterity, enhanced mobility through wristed instruments, stability of the camera platform, three-dimensional visualization, motion scaling, and better ergonomics. Consequently, there is a signi /uniFB01 cant potential for RAPs in CRS, particularly in the bony pelvis, where the increased dexterity and wristed instruments allow additional freedom of movement. 2

The adoption of RAPs is thought to facilitate the uptake of MIS. However, one study suggested that rather than reducing open surgery, RAPs have instead reduced the proportion of laparoscopic surgeries. 3 While the use of RAP has increased in the /uniFB01 eld of CRS, little is known about the use of RAP in more complex colorectal patients. 4 Our aim for this study was to evaluate any trends in the adoption of RAPs in CRS for higher risk and acutely ill patients over a 6-year period. To do this, we evaluated the proportion of laparoscopic, robotic, and planned open cases over time using the American College of Surgeons

(ACS) National Surgical Quality Improvement Project (NSQIP). The ACS NSQIP has included RAPs as an operative approach since 2013, making it an appropriate choice for our analysis.

We queried the ACS NSQIP database between 2013 and 2018 and identi /uniFB01 ed 192 454 patients who underwent colectomy. Using the ' surgical approach ' variable, the patients were divided into the following groups: Planned open, Laparoscopic, and Robotic assisted. Unplanned conversions to open surgery were categorized separately. The proportion of colectomies performed using RAPs, as well as laparoscopic and planned open approaches, was calculated for each year. Yearly trend in the use of open and RAP was compared to that of laparoscopy.

A subgroup analysis was performed for the patients who underwent a colorectal resection requiring coloproctostomy. Finally, the cohort was divided into groups based on age (18-49, 50-64, 65-79, and 80+), gender, body mass index (BMI) (<18.5, 18.5-24.9, 25-29.9, 30-34.9, and 35+), and American Society of Anesthesiology (ASA) classi /uniFB01 cation (I-V). The prevalence of robotic surgery was compared over time across gender, age and BMI categories, and ASA classi /uniFB01 cations using logistic regression.

Of the 192 454 patients included in the analysis, 93 574 (48.6%) patients underwent laparoscopic colectomy, 69 182 (36%) patients underwent planned open colectomy, and 15 044 (7.8%) patients underwent colectomy using RAP. The use of laparoscopic approach remained stable over the studied period (48.2-49.7%), whereas the use of RAP increased signi /uniFB01 cantly from 2.8% in 2013 to 11.4% in 2018, accounting for a 307% increase (Figure 1). There was a concomitant decline in the use of open surgery from 40.8% to 33% during this time (Figure 1). The increase in RAP was also noticeable for the subgroup requiring coloproctostomy, which rose from 5.6 to 18.2% (Figure 1). The occurrence of conversion to open cases did not change over time. The observed increase in the use of RAP and the decrease in the use of open approach were statistically different from the trend in the use of laparoscopy for the entire cohort, as well as the patient subgroup requiring coloproctostomies ( P < .01). Furthermore, the use of RAP also increased within all gender, age, BMI, and ASA groups during the study period (Figure 2). The rate of yearly increase was statistically signi /uniFB01 cant for all subgroups ( P < .01).

The /uniFB01 ndings of this study are con /uniFB01 rmed by a similar study by Schootman et al, who studied the National Inpatient Sample from 2010 to 2012, and revealed an increased adoption of robotic surgery, particularly in rectal cancer resections. 4 In that patient population, most patients

underwent open surgery (52.9%), followed by laparoscopic (36.3%) and robotic (1.3%). The present study highlights increased adoption of minimally invasive techniques, to the point that a plurality of colorectal resections is being performed laparoscopically, and a majority minimally invasively. Whereas prior studies using NSQIP showed increasing adoption of laparoscopic techniques in CRS, the present study shows a stable percentage of cases performed laparoscopically, indicating a plateau in the adoption of conventional laparoscopic techniques (Figure 1). 1

Interestingly, in the present study, the increasing use of minimally invasive CRS is being driven by the adoption of RAPs and concomitant reduction of open operations, rather than increasing use of conventional laparoscopy. We observed a 307% increase in the proportion of robotic surgeries across the study period. There was a signi /uniFB01 cant increase in robotic operations for cases involving low rectal resections also, with concomitant reduction in open surgery. These data run counter to the /uniFB01 ndings by Armijjo et al, which suggest that the increase in robotic surgery is predominantly driven by a decreasing proportion of laparoscopic operations. 3

We also observed an increase in RAPs across multiple patient subgroups (age, ASA, and BMI). The increase in the use of RAPs for patients with increased age, BMI, and ASA classi /uniFB01 cation signi /uniFB01 es that not only is it being used widely but it is also being utilized on more complex, higher risk patients. Conventional laparoscopy has been increasingly used for more complex patients with higher ASA and is shown to have lower morbidity rates and faster recovery when compared to open procedures. This study demonstrates an analogous adoption of robotic surgery in medically complex patients, leading to broader overall use of MIS.

This is the /uniFB01 rst study, to our knowledge, to evaluate the trends in the adoption RAP over this long of a period.

There are several limitations to our study. This is a retrospective review of a large national database, which is subject to selection bias and unmeasured confounding effects. In addition, using a large administrative database has shown to have a rate of coding error approximately 1%. Also, we recognize that even though NSQIP collects data from over 600 hospitals, it may not be a nationally representative cross-section.

Despite the weaknesses, this study shows that the RAP is increasingly adopted for colorectal resections, with a concurrent decrease in planned open cases. Robotic platforms are increasingly used or higher risk, older and obese patients, allowing more patients to receive MIS.
